aa(lp17
VSo I've been thinking about that problem,
p18
aVand a thinker who has  helped me think about it
p19
aVis a guy named Joseph Soloveitchik, who was a rabbi
p20
aVwho wrote a book called "The Lonely Man Of Faith" in 1965.
p21
aVSoloveitchik said there are two sides of our natures,
p22
aVwhich he called Adam I and Adam II.
p23
aVAdam I is the worldly, ambitious,
p24
aVexternal side of our nature.
p25
aVHe wants to build, create, create companies,
p26
aVcreate innovation.
p27
aVAdam II is the humble side of our nature.
p28
aVAdam II wants not only  to do good but to be good,
p29
aVto live in a way internally
p30
aVthat honors God, creation and our possibilities.
p31
aVAdam I wants to conquer the world.
p32
aVAdam II wants to hear  a calling and obey the world.
p33
aVAdam I savors accomplishment.
p34
aVAdam II savors inner  consistency and strength.
p35
aVAdam I asks how things work.
p36
aVAdam II asks why we're here.
p37
aVAdam I's motto is "success."
p38
aVAdam II's motto is "love, redemption and return."
p39
aa(lp40
VAnd Soloveitchik argued  that these two sides
p41
aVof our nature are  at war with each other.
p42
aVWe live in perpetual self-confrontation
p43
aVbetween the external success and the internal value.
p44
aVAnd the tricky thing,  I'd say, about these
p45
aVtwo sides of our nature is they work
p46
aVby different logics.
p47
aVThe external logic is  an economic logic:
p48
aVinput leads to output,  risk leads to reward.
p49
aVThe internal side of our nature
p50
aVis a moral logic and  often an inverse logic.
p51
aVYou have to give to receive.
p52
aVYou have to surrender  to something outside yourself
p53
aVto gain strength within yourself.
p54
aVYou have to conquer the desire to get what you want.
p55
aVIn order to fulfill yourself, you have to forget yourself.
p56
aVIn order to find yourself,  you have to lose yourself.
p57
aa(lp58
VWe happen to live in a society  that favors Adam I,
p59
aVand often neglects Adam II.
p60
aVAnd the problem is, that turns you into a shrewd animal
p61
aVwho treats life as a game,
p62
aVand you become a cold,  calculating creature
p63
aVwho slips into a sort of mediocrity
p64
aVwhere you realize there's a difference
p65
aVbetween your desired  self and your actual self.
p66
aVYou're not earning the sort of eulogy you want,
p67
aVyou hope someone will give to you.
p68
aVYou don't have the  depth of conviction.
p69
aVYou don't have an emotional sonorousness.
p70
aVYou don't have  commitment to tasks
p71
aVthat would take more than a lifetime to commit.
